<div id="course_syllabus" style="margin-bottom: 10px;" class="user_content">
  <p>Harvard University Extension School <br>RELI E-1704 (15068)<br>Fall Term 2017 <br>Thursdays 5:30-7:30 pm</p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><em><span style="font-size: 36pt;">Zen Stories</span></em></h2>
<p><img style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" src="/courses/32815/files/4145019/preview?verifier=zqWfb9VOMlScJhgX8fooyqHSNvFUMTO2mtqz1TU8" alt="zen-stories.png" data-api-endpoint="https://canvas.harvard.edu/api/v1$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/zen-stories.png?canvas_download=1&amp;canvas_qs_verifier=9AGMB2tJswl2qAPVw5skFG4gdaJewzAVqT3Q4Hnx" data-api-returntype="File"></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Instructor: Dr. Christopher Queen, Lecturer in Extension<br>99 West Street, Wendell, MA 01379 Phone 978-544-0216<br>E-mail: <a href="mailto:christopher_queen@harvard.edu">christopher_queen@harvard.edu</a></p>
<h3 style="text-align: center;">Course Description</h3>
<p>The word Zen derives from an ancient Buddhist term for meditation.  Zen takes many forms: sitting quietly; looking deeply; and breathing, walking, and working for inner peace and social change.   By sharing stories of simple beginners and great masters, from the Buddha and his followers to modern figures like Thich Nhat Hanh, Bernie Glassman, and angel Kyodo williams, we will trace many pathways of Zen.  Keeping an online journal, drafting and polishing short essays, critiquing readings and films, and meeting special guests, we will encounter Zen.  No previous study of Buddhism is required.</p>
<p>     <strong>Zen Stories is taught in seminar style</strong>: we will sit in a circle or around a table to facilitate class discussion.  The readings offer a general introduction to Buddhism, meditation, and a wide sampling of Zen narratives told by women and men from ancient to modern times.  Each class will include a five-minute period of formal mindfulness in the context of academic discussion and analysis. Films and guests will offer first-hand testimony on the Zen life. </p>
<p>     <strong>The course grade</strong> will be based on three graded essays (20 percent each), class participation (20 percent, based on weekly online journaling; first, non-graded essay; and drafts for the second and third essays), and a final exam (20 percent).  Students will learn about the history and literature of Zen Buddhism while cultivating skills of analysis and interpretation appropriate to the study of religion.</p>
<p><strong>The course syllabus</strong> information is included on this page. You may also <a id="" class="instructure_file_link instructure_scribd_file" title="Zen Stories Syllabus 2017.docx" href="/courses/32815/files/4146722/download?verifier=OUa744Mided3smVo0Nxg0rLozq1Aak2ufC8VnV0l&amp;wrap=1" target="" data-api-endpoint="https://canvas.harvard.edu/api/v1$IMS-CC-FILEBASE$/Zen%20Stories%20Syllabus.docx?canvas_download=1&amp;canvas_qs_verifier=fb7i8PLxCNLssU8KQPTZj6sEq8QPtIosT3LruFk4" data-api-returntype="File">download the syllabus</a> for offline reference. </p>
<h3 style="text-align: center;"><img src="/courses/32815/files/4146557/preview?verifier=mGFGnoBnkg7SLUxBSLVH8rCwFa86iqn3YtI6EYSn" alt="requiredtexts.png" width="91" height="91"></h3>
<h3 style="text-align: center;">Required Texts</h3>
<h3 style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Available at Harvard Coop and online.</span></h3>
<p style="text-align: center;">Herrigel, <em>Zen in the Art of Archery </em>(ZAA)<br>Kozak, <em>The Everything Buddhism Book </em>(BB)<br>Nhat Hanh, <em>The Miracle of Mindfulness </em>(MM)<br>Reps and Senzaki, <em>Zen Flesh, Zen Bones </em>(ZZ)<br>Caplow and Moon, <em>The Hidden Lamp </em>(HL)<br>Glassman and Fields, <em>Instructions to the Cook </em>(IC)</p>
<h3 style="text-align: center;">Meetings and Assignments (readings are for date listed)</h3>
<table width="100%">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Aug</td>
<td>31</td>
<td>Beginnings: The course. What is Zen?</td>
<td>Student survey; ZAA vii-81</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Sep</td>
