<h3 style="text-align: center;">Online Journaling</h3>
<p><strong><em>The course website hosts an <a href="/courses/32815/discussion_topics">online discussion</a></em></strong> of the themes of the course.  Each week, students will post a short reflection on the readings, class discussion, or their own work.  This may evolve into a discussion or simply stand as a record of our evolving insights.  The weekly posts earn participation credits toward the course grade.</p>
<h3 style="text-align: center;">Writing Assignments</h3>
<p><strong><em>            Writing-intensive courses at Harvard Extension School</em></strong> offer students the opportunity to develop their writing skills in the context of a particular academic discipline, and they all feature common elements.  Students will develop core writing skills, as defined by the instructor, in the discipline of the course; complete multiple writing assignments of varying lengths, at least 2 of which must be revised; produce a minimum of 10-12 pages of writing, exclusive of the required drafts, over the course of the term; meet at least once in individual conference (in person, by phone, or electronically) with the instructor or TA to discuss writing in progress; and receive detailed feedback on their drafts and revisions, on both content and expression.</p>
<p><strong><em>             Please avoid plagiarism, </em></strong><em>the use of another writer's words or ideas without proper citation. </em>To learn about correction citation of sources for your essays in Zen Stories, please consult the<em> Harvard Guide to Using Sources</em> <a href="http://usingsources.fas.harvard.edu">http://usingsources.fas.harvard.edu</a> and select the style of citation you prefer.  </p>
<p>            You are responsible for understanding Harvard Extension School policies on academic integrity (<a href="http://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/student-conduct/academic-integrity">www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/student-conduct/academic-integrity</a>) and how to use sources responsibly. Not knowing the rules, misunderstanding the rules, running out of time, submitting the wrong draft, or being overwhelmed with multiple demands are not acceptable excuses. There are no excuses for failure to uphold academic integrity. To support your learning about academic citation rules, please visit the Harvard Extension School Tips to Avoid Plagiarism (<a href="http://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/tips-avoid-plagiarism">www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/tips-avoid-plagiarism</a>), where you'll find links to the Harvard Guide to Using Sources and two free online 15-minute tutorials to test your knowledge of academic citation policy. The tutorials are anonymous open-learning tools.</p>
<p>            <strong><em>Writing Center.</em> </strong>Registered Extension School students can get help with many writing-related issues, such as organization, focus, style, grammar, and citation of sources.  Tutors offer feedback on writing assignments directly related to Extension School coursework. When you meet with a tutor, you should bring a written description of the assignment you are working on, as well as any writing you have done for the assignment.  You may schedule an appointment through <a href="http://www.extension.harvard.edu/login">online services</a> up to a week in advance. Students may have up to two tutorials a week, up to a total of seven tutorials a term.</p>
<p><strong><em>General directions for essays.</em>  </strong>Drafts and final essays are due <em>in the website drop box</em> at midnight on the due date.  In order to remain on schedule, late drafts cannot be read; late papers will be penalized one-half letter-grade per day.  All drafts and papers will be marked and returned electronically.  Essays should be typed double-spaced with 1-inch margins in 12-pt. type; have an original title; and strictly adhere to page limitations.  Subsections may be numbered or titled. </p>
<p>            These essays are very short.  So you will have to give MORE attention to your choice of words, the meaning of each sentence, the coherence of each paragraph, and the flow of your argument or narrative.  It all needs to hang together!  Your essays should reflect your dialogue with course readings and discussions, as well as perspectives you bring to the assignment.</p>
<h3 style="text-align: center;">The Final Examination</h3>
<p>The final examination, given during the last class, is an opportunity to show your mastery of basic themes and readings in the course.  A review sheet describing the nature of the exam and suggesting study strategies will be provided on December 3.</p>
<h3 style="text-align: center;">Accessibility</h3>
<p>The Extension School is committed to providing an accessible academic community. The Accessibility Office offers a variety of accommodations and services to students with documented disabilities. Please visit <a id="" class="" title="" href="http://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/disability-services-accessibility" target="">www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/disability-services-accessibility</a> for more information.</p>
<p> </p>
